To derive anything from S, you must apply the only rule for S:

  S → NT43 NT61

Both NT43 and NT61 must each eventually produce at least one terminal (there are no ε‐productions). Thus any string in L(G) from S has length ≥ 2. The target string “t6” has length 1, so it cannot be generated.

The shortest strings S can produce are of length 2 (e.g. NT43 → 't40' and NT61 → 't33' gives "t40 t33"). It cannot produce just "t33."

3. NT43 → NT83 NT77

4. NT83 → NT86 NT79  
   – NT79 → “t36”  (11th token)

5. NT86 → NT82 NT76  
   – NT76 → “t74”  (10th token)

6. NT82 → NT62 NT0  
   – NT0 → “t42”  (9th token)

7. NT62 → NT45 NT32  

   • NT45 → NT28 NT3 covering “t25 t2 t87”  
     – NT28 → NT27 NT59 → “t25” “t2”  
     – NT3 → “t87”

   • NT32 → NT56 NT9 covering “t42 t6 t21 t25 t87”  
     – NT56 → NT29 NT21 → “t42” “t6”  
     – NT9 → NT68 NT16 → “t21” + (NT27 NT3 → “t25” “t87”)

Putting it all together reproduces exactly  
t25 t2 t87 t42 t6 t21 t25 t87 t42 t74 t36 t42 t33.
